{"title_page": "One Way Ticket (1997 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = One Way Ticket\n| image          = \n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Richard Franklin (director)|Richard Franklin]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Ian Bradley]]\n*[[Andrew Brooke]]\n*[[Kris Noble]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Karin Altmann]]\n*[[Michael Brindley]]\n}}\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Peter Phelps]]\n*[[Rachel Blakely]]\n*[[Chris Haywood]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Nerida Tyson-Chew]]\n| cinematography = Ellery Ryan\n| editing        = David Pulbrook\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Grundy Television Productions]]\n*[[Nine Network Australia]]\n}}\n| distributor    = \n| released       = \n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''One Way Ticket''''' is a 1997 Australian [[television film|made-for-television]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Richard Franklin (director)|Richard Franklin]]. The film was inspired by real events in the life of prison officer [[Heather Parker (prison officer)|Heather Parker]], who assisted in the escape of [[Peter Gibb]] and [[Archie Butterly]].<ref>http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/find-a-film/detail.aspx?tid=8891</ref><ref>http://www.australiantelevision.net/telemovies/1997.html</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA criminal languishing in jail embarks on a torrid affair with a female guard. However, events take a sinister turn as she becomes increasingly besotted, and news of their romance becomes public \u2013 leading to the collapse of her marriage. Desperate, she agrees to help the crook escape, only to start doubting his commitment.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Peter Phelps]] as Mick Webb\n*[[Rachel Blakely]] as Deborah Carter\n*[[Chris Haywood]] as Bertie\n*[[Jane Hall (actress)|Jane Hall]] as Kate Stark\n*[[Joseph Spano]] as Kaiser\n*[[Adriano Cortese]] as Tumeo\n*[[Russell Fletcher]] as Geoff\n*[[Marie-Louise Jolicoeur]] as Maureen\n*[[Samuel Johnson]] as Jimmie\n*[[Doug Bowles]] as Preece\n*[[Regina Gaigalas]] as Lena\n*[[Richard E. Young]] as Louis\n*[[Sally Lightfoot (actress)|Sally Lightfoot]] as Pam\n*[[Dennis Miller (Australian actor)|Dennis Miller]] as Alf\n*[[Elspeth Ballantyne]] as Elizabeth\n*[[Richard Moir]] as Governor\n*[[Frank Gallacher]] as Macca\n*[[Troy Rowley]] as Mouse\n*[[Terry Gill]] as Buddle\n*[[Elly Varrenti]] as Mags\n\n==Production==\nSome filming took place at St. Andrews Hotel, St. Andrews, Victoria, Australia.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0119834/locations?ref_=ttfc_sa_5</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0119834}}\n\n{{Richard Franklin}}\n\n[[Category:1997 television films]]\n[[Category:Australian television films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Richard Franklin (director)]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Nerida Tyson-Chew]]\n\n\n{{Australia-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = One Way Ticket\n| image          = \n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Richard Franklin (director)|Richard Franklin]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Ian Bradley]]\n*[[Andrew Brooke]]\n*[[Kris Noble]]\n}}\n| writer         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Karin Altmann]]\n*[[Michael Brindley]]\n}}\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Peter Phelps]]\n*[[Rachel Blakely]]\n*[[Chris Haywood]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Nerida Tyson-Chew]]\n| cinematography = [[Ellery Ryan]]\n| editing        = [[David Pulbrook]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Grundy Television Productions]]\n*[[Nine Network Australia]]\n}}\n| distributor    = \n| released       = \n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''One Way Ticket''''' is a 1997 Australian [[television film|made-for-television]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Richard Franklin (director)|Richard Franklin]]. The film was inspired by real events in the life of prison officer [[Heather Parker (prison officer)|Heather Parker]], who assisted in the escape of [[Peter Gibb]] and [[Archie Butterly]].<ref>http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/find-a-film/detail.aspx?tid=8891</ref><ref>http://www.australiantelevision.net/telemovies/1997.html</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA criminal languishing in jail embarks on a torrid affair with a female guard. However, events take a sinister turn as she becomes increasingly besotted, and news of their romance becomes public \u2013 leading to the collapse of her marriage. Desperate, she agrees to help the crook escape, only to start doubting his commitment.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Peter Phelps]] as Mick Webb\n*[[Rachel Blakely]] as Deborah Carter\n*[[Chris Haywood]] as Bertie\n*[[Jane Hall (actress)|Jane Hall]] as Kate Stark\n*[[Joseph Spano]] as Kaiser\n*[[Adriano Cortese]] as Tumeo\n*[[Russell Fletcher]] as Geoff\n*[[Marie-Louise Jolicoeur]] as Maureen\n*[[Samuel Johnson]] as Jimmie\n*[[Doug Bowles]] as Preece\n*[[Regina Gaigalas]] as Lena\n*[[Richard E. Young]] as Louis\n*[[Sally Lightfoot (actress)|Sally Lightfoot]] as Pam\n*[[Dennis Miller (Australian actor)|Dennis Miller]] as Alf\n*[[Elspeth Ballantyne]] as Elizabeth\n*[[Richard Moir]] as Governor\n*[[Frank Gallacher]] as Macca\n*[[Troy Rowley]] as Mouse\n*[[Terry Gill]] as Buddle\n*[[Elly Varrenti]] as Mags\n\n==Production==\nSome filming took place at St. Andrews Hotel, St. Andrews, Victoria, Australia.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0119834/locations?ref_=ttfc_sa_5</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0119834}}\n\n{{Richard Franklin}}\n\n[[Category:1997 television films]]\n[[Category:Australian television films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Richard Franklin (director)]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Nerida Tyson-Chew]]\n\n\n{{Australia-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Way_Ticket_(1997_film)"}
