irlight, New Zealand|Fairlight]] \u2013 [[Kingston, New Zealand|Kingston]] || Closed completely 1982 except: <br> Kingston \u2013 Fairlight (Otago) operated by [[Kingston Flyer]] Ltd, Invercargill \u2013 Makarewa part of Wairio Branch\n|-\n| [[Bluff Branch|Mokomoko Harbour Branch]] || [[Awarua, Invercargill|Awarua]] \u2013 [[Mokomoko Harbour]] || Closed 1875, Standard gauge 1435mm from 1866, connected to [[Bluff Branch]]\n|-\n| [[Mossburn Branch]] || Lumsden \u2013 [[Mossburn]] || Closed 1982\n|-\n| [[Tuatapere Branch|Riverton Branch/Tuatapere Branch/Orawia Branch]] || Makarewa \u2013 [[Thornbury, New Zealand|Thornbury]] \u2013 [[Riverton, New Zealand|Riverton]] \u2013 [[Tuatapere]] \u2013 [[Orawia]] || Closed Tuatapere \u2013 Orawia 1970, Riverton \u2013 Tuatapere 1976, Thornbury \u2013 Riverton 1978 <br> Makarewa \u2013 Thornbury part of Wairio Branch\n|-\n| [[Tokanui Branch|Tokanui (or Seaward Bush) Branch]] || Invercargill \u2013 [[Tokanui]] || Closed 1966\n|-\n| [[Waikaia Branch]] || [[Riversdale, New Zealand|Riversdale]] \u2013 [[Waikaia]] || Closed 1959\n|-\n| [[Waikaka Branch]] || [[McNab, New Zealand|McNab]] \u2013 [[Waikaka]] ||Closed 1962\n|-\n| '''[[Wairio Branch|Wairio Branch/Ohai Industrial Line]]''' || Invercargill \u2013 Makarewa \u2013 Thornbury \u2013 [[Wairio]] \u2013 [[Nightcaps]] \u2013 [[Ohai]] || Freight only, mothballed beyond Nightcaps\n|-\n| [[Wyndham Branch]] || [[Edendale, New Zealand|Edendale]] \u2013 [[Wyndham, New Zealand|Wyndham]] \u2013 [[Glenham, New Zealand|Glenham]] || Closed Wyndham \u2013 Glenham 1930, Edendale \u2013 Wyndham 1962\n|}\n\n===Private lines===\nParts of the network were constructed by private companies, and most were unsuccessful. All except the Whakatane Board Mills line and the [[Sanson Tramway]] were later acquired by the government. The most successful was the [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway]], which operated between Wellington and Longburn (near Palmerston North) from 1885 to 1908. After the WMR, perhaps the best-known private railway was the [[New Zealand Midland Railway Company]], which constructed parts of the Midland, Nelson and West Coast lines. After the company was dissolved in 1900 the railway lines and their construction were taken over by the government. Some lines were built by companies for access such as to coal mines, and by local government bodies.\n* [[Cape Foulwind Branch]]\n* [[Castlecliff Railway]]\n* [[Fernhill Branch]]\n* [[Hutt Park Railway]]\n* [[Kaitangata Line]] \t\n* [[Kakanui]] McDonald Limeworks Branch\n* [[Kurow Branch]] ([[Duntroon, New Zealand|Duntroon]] \u2013 [[Hakataramea]] portion)\n* Mokai Tramway (TTT Co line, [[Putaruru]] to Mokai near [[Lake Taupo]])\n* [[New Zealand Midland Railway Company|New Zealand Midland Railway Company Limited]]\n* [[Ohai Railway Board]]\n* [[Port Chalmers Branch|Port Chalmers Railway Company Limited]]\n* [[Riccarton Racecourse Siding]]\n* [[Methven Branch|Rakaia and Ashburton Forks Railway Limited]]\n* [[Sanson Tramway]]\n* [[Taratu]] Railway (Lovells Flat) \n* Thames Valley and Rotorua Railway Company\n* Waronui (Coal) Railway (Milton)\n* [[Waimate Branch|Waimate Gorge Branch]]\n* [[Waimea Plains Railway]]\n* [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway|Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company Limited]]\n* [[Whakatane Board Mills Line]]\n* [[Wilton Colleries Line]]\n\n===Significant proposals===\n\nMany railway lines have been proposed, especially in the 19th century, but never constructed. An 1873 map indicated that it was intended to link up all the current and authorised routes into a national network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://natlib.govt.nz/records/21672448|title=Sketch map of the Colony of New Zealand shewing authorised and proposed railway lines|last=|first=|date=1873|website=National Library|publisher=Department of Lands and Survey.|access-date=}}</ref> Some proposals have been particularly significant due to their extent, publicity, or how close they came to being realised (in some cases, the [[track bed]] was built).  Some significant proposals include:\n* [[Auckland Airport Line]] \u2013 an extension of the [[Onehunga Branch]] to [[Auckland Airport]], and/or a link from the airport to the [[North Island Main Trunk|NIMT]] at [[Puhinui Railway Station|Puhinui]]. Other options also mooted.\n* [[Auckland]] [[City Rail Link]] \u2013 underground rail link under central Auckland. Now an active project\n*[[Avondale - Southdown Line]] (land corridor owned by KiwiRail)\n*[[Canterbury Interior Main Line]]\n*Connection of the [[Catlins River Branch]] and the [[Tokanui Branch]]\n*[[Cromwell]] \u2013 [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]], proposed connection with the Kingston Branch extension before Otago Central Railway route chosen.\n*[[Culverden]] \u2013 [[Reefton]] line\n*[[Culverden]] to [[Tophouse]], with branches from there to Nelson and [[Blenheim, New Zealand|Blenheim]]\n*Dunedin Peninsula and Ocean Beach railway extension to Portobello and Taiaroa Heads.\n*Extension of the [[East Coast Main Trunk Railway]] to link [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]] and [[Rotorua]] by going inland from [[Opotiki]] up the Waiweka Gorge to the [[Moutohora Branch]]. So would link the [[Bay of Plenty]] to Gisborne and [[Palmerston North]] via the [[Palmerston North \u2013 Gisborne Line]].  \n*[[Fairlie Branch]] \u2013 extension 27&nbsp;km beyond Eversley, proposals to terminate the line in [[Burkes Pass]] \n*East Cape tourist line via Hicks Bay <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/national-news/90227179/Chinese-investors-show-interest-in-East-Cape-tourist-rail-project|title=Cape tourist rail project|first=Simon|last=Hendery|date=9 March 2017|work=[[The Southland Times]]}}</ref>\n*[[Haywards\u2013Plimmerton Line]] between the [[Hutt Valley Line]] and the [[Kapiti Line]].\n*[[Kakahi, New Zealand|Kakahi]] \u2013 [[P\u016bkawa]] ([[Lake Taupo]]) line\n*[[Kennington]] \u2013 [[Waikiwi]] deviation to [[Invercargill]]\n*[[Kingston Branch (New Zealand)|Kingston Branch]] \u2013 extension to  [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]]\n*[[Kirikopuni]] \u2013 [[Kaikohe]] line\n*[[Kurow Branch]] \u2013 extension beyond [[Hakataramea]]\n*[[Lewis Pass]] Railway ([[Reefton]] to [[Culverden]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19070813.2.23&l=mi&e=-------10--1----0-all |title=Papers Past \u2014 Evening Post \u2014 13 Hereturik\u014dk\u0101 1907 \u2014 RAILWAY ROUTE |website=Paperspast.natlib.govt.nz |date=13 August 1907 |accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Little River Branch]] \u2013 extension to [[Akaroa]]\n*[[Marsden Point Branch]] and its Waipu precursor\n*[[Martinborough Branch]]\n*[[Mossburn Branch]] \u2013 extension to [[Te Anau]]\n*[[Motueka]] to Tadmor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NEM18861111.2.13 |title=Papers Past \u2014 Nelson Evening Mail \u2014 11 November 1886 \u2014 THE MOTUEKA-TADMOII RAILWAY ROUTE |website=Paperspast.natlib.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson railway proposals#Nelson\u2013Blenheim Line|Nelson \u2013 Blenheim line]]\n*Extension of the [[Nelson Section]] through the [[Buller Gorge]] to the [[West Coast, New Zealand|West Coast]].\n*[[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]] to [[Cobden, New Zealand|Cobden]] and [[Westport, New Zealand|Westport]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzlii.org/nz/legis/hist_act/ncawrla186630v1866n33504.pdf |format=PDF |title=New Zealand : Anno Tricesimo Victoriae Reginae : No. 33 |website=Nzlii.org |accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n*North Shore Line \u2013 from central Auckland (Britomart) to the North Shore, and extended northward on the route currently occupied by the [[Northern Busway, Auckland|Northern Busway]]\n*[[Okaihau Branch]] \u2013 extension to [[Rangiahua]] and [[Kaitaia]]\n*[[Opunake Branch]] \u2013 sub-branch from [[Kapuni]] to [[Manaia, Taranaki|Manaia]]; extension to [[New Plymouth]]\n*[[Otago Central Railway]] \u2013 extension to [[Wanaka]]\n*Paengaroa \u2013 Rotorua line\n*[[Paeroa\u2013Pokeno Line]] \n*Ross \u2013 Haast, including rebuilding to heavy rail of the Stewart and Chapman tramway to Lake Ianthe State Forest. \n*[[Roxburgh Branch]] \u2013 connection from [[Roxburgh, New Zealand|Roxburgh]] to the Otago Central Railway in [[Alexandra, New Zealand|Alexandra]]\n*Sockburn-Styx deviation and industrial line.\n*[[Taupo Railway Proposals]] \u2013 connections from Rotorua, Kinleith or Murupara branches\n*[[Te Aro Extension]] \u2013 extension to Island Bay\n*[[Waiau Branch]] \u2013 extension to [[Kaikoura]]\n*[[Waimate Branch]] \u2013 extension of the Waihao Downs line\n*[[Wainuiomata Railway Proposals|Wainuiomata Branch]] \u2013 from the [[Hutt Valley Line|Hutt Valley]] section of the [[Wairarapa Line]] to the suburb.  \n*[[Wairau Valley]] Railway from Tophouse to Blenheim<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=MEX19130702.2.14 |title=Papers Past \u2014 Marlborough Express \u2014 2 July 1913 \u2014 THE WAIRAU VALLEY RAILWAY |website=Paperspast.natlib.govt.nz |date=2 July 1913 |accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Westport, New Zealand|Westport]] to [[Charleston, New Zealand|Charleston]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=NENZC18670704.2.8&l=mi&e=-------10--1----0-- |title=Papers Past \u2014 Nelson Examiner and New Zealand Chronicle \u2014 4 H\u014dngongoi 1867 \u2014 WESTPORT AND CHARLESTON RAILWAY |website=Paperspast.natlib.govt.nz |date= |accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nSee also [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=HNS19100823.2.41.1&e=-------10--1----0-- Hawera & Normanby Star, Volume LVII, 23 August 1910, Page 5] for a '''list of railways authorised, proposed and under construction, with estimated cost of completing them as at 1 April 1910''', many of which were not built.\n\n==Nelson \u2013 Blenheim notional railway==\nThe [[Nelson - Blenheim notional railway]] was created in November 1957 to help manage the political backlash from the 1955 closure of the isolated [[Nelson Section]].  [[New Zealand State Highway 6|State Highway 6]] between Nelson and Blenheim was deemed by law to be an NZR railway for the purposes of calculating passenger and freight rates between railway stations in the South Island and Nelson or other places on the notional railway.  Passengers and freight travelled by road, with the difference between the road carrier's rates and railway rates subsidised by the government.  Rail rates were significantly cheaper than road rates, so the scheme provided significant benefits to its users, while imposing significant costs on the government.  The scheme lasted for 22 years, being withdrawn in October 1977.\n\n==Bush tramways==\nThese were lines principally constructed to haul timber or minerals, often in isolated areas. A variety of gauges was used, including the New Zealand standard {{RailGauge|3'6\"}}. Typical bush trams were more lightly constructed than ordinary rail lines and had steeper gradients and sharper curves. With the low speeds that were commonplace, rolling stock and locomotives were generally built to lighter standards than main-line vehicles. It was not uncommon for road vehicles to be adapted, either as haulage power or rolling stock. As road vehicles became more suited for these operations the trams gradually faded away and none are now operating.\n\nA prominent example of a [[Tramway (industrial)|bush tramway]] was the [[Taupo railway proposals#Mokai Tramway|Taupo Totara Timber Company's line between Putaruru and Mokai]], and an example of a mineral tramway was the [[Dun Mountain Railway]].\n\nOther bush and mineral tramways included -{{expand list|date=July 2016}}\n\n=== North Island ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Route !! Usage\n|-\n|[[Piha Tramway]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Messrs. Smyth Brothers' Tramway|Smyth Brothers' Tramway]]\n|[[Kennedy's Bay]], [[Coromandel Peninsula]]\n|1897\u20131908 3&nbsp;ft\n|-\n|[[Waiorongomai Tramway|Piako County Tramway]]\n|[[Kaimai Range]]\n|1884\u20131924 2&nbsp;ft 9in\n|-\n|[[Ellis and Burnand Tramway, Ongarue|Ellis and Burnand Tramway]]\n|[[Ongarue River|Ongarue]]\n|1922\u20131958\n|-\n|[[Knight's tram, Raurimu|Knight's tram]]\n|[[Raurimu Spiral|Raurimu]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Makatote Tramway]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Taringamotu Tramway]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Price's Bush Tramway]]\n|[[Hutt Valley]] to [[Waikanae]]\n| \n|-\n|[[Driving Creek Railway]]\n|[[Coromandel, New Zealand|Coromandel]]\n|Tourist attraction\n|}\n\n=== South Island ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Route !! Usage\n|-\n|[[Bell Hill mill tramway]]\n|  || \n|-\n|[[Koranui Incline]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Mount Somers Branch#Construction|Mount Somers Tramway]]\n|\n|1886\u20131963\n|-\n|tramways linking to [[Ross Branch#Stations|Ross Branch]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Kokiri Tramway]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Fortification, New Zealand#Tramway|Fortification sawmill tramway]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Port Craig, New Zealand#Tramway|Port Craig tramway]]\n|Port Craig, [[Percy Burn Viaduct]], [[Wairaurahiri River]]\n|1919\u20131928 Marlborough Timber Co\n|}\n\n==Street tramways==\nMajor street tramway networks were constructed in [[Auckland]], [[Wellington]], [[Christchurch]] and [[Dunedin]], with smaller operations in [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]], [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]], [[New Plymouth]], [[Wanganui]],  [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]] and [[Invercargill]]. Employing horse, steam or electric power, they operated in most cases until the 1950s when improved buses saw most of the tracks scrapped. Urban tram operations, built from scratch as tourist attractions, have more recently been restarted in Christchurch (1995)  Auckland (2011), and Wanganui (2013). See [[Trams in New Zealand]].\n\n==Heritage and Private railways==\nA large number of societies operate [[List of New Zealand railway museums and heritage lines|working heritage railway lines and museums]]. Most of these are run largely or wholly by volunteer labour, except commercially operated private trust owned [[Dunedin Railways]] in Dunedin, which employs paid staff.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stott|first=Bob|title=Rails through the bush|publisher=Southern Press|date=1973}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{NZR_Lines}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of railway lines by country|New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in New Zealand| ]]\n[[Category:New Zealand railway-related lists|Railway lines]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in New Zealand|Railway lines in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|wikimedia list article}}\n{{NZ rail}}\n\nThe railway network in [[New Zealand]] consists of four main lines, seven secondary lines{{Clarify|date=October 2014|reason=The tables list 5 main lines and 6 secondary lines}} and numerous short [[branch line]]s in almost every region. It links all major urban centres except [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]], [[Taupo]], [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]], [[Whakatane]] and (since 2012) [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]]. The network is owned and managed by [[KiwiRail]]. The network was constructed from 1863 onwards, mostly by government bodies, initially [[Provinces of New Zealand|provincial governments]] and later central government (usually the [[New Zealand Ministry of Works|Public Works Department]]). In 1993 [[Tranz Rail|New Zealand Rail Limited]] was privatised (and later renamed Tranz Rail), with the New Zealand Railways Corporation retaining the land (due to [[Treaty of Waitangi]] claims on land taken for railway construction). In 2003 the government renationalised the network. KiwiRail operates all freight and a small number of passenger services primarily for tourists on certain routes in both islands; Transdev operates Auckland Transport 'AT Metro' suburban passenger trains in Auckland and Metlink passenger trains in the Wellington region; Dunedin Railways (formerly Taieri Gorge Railway) operates tourist passenger trains in Dunedin.\n\n==New Zealand national rail network==\n[[File:NorthIsland rrMap v02.svg|thumb|right|North Island rail network map (as of 2006)]]\n[[File:SouthIsland rrMap v02.svg|thumb|right|South Island rail network map (as of 2006)]]\nLines in '''bold type''' are currently operated by KiwiRail\n\n===Main trunk lines===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Route !! Length !! Usage\n|-\n| '''[[North Island Main Trunk]]''' || [[Wellington]] \u2013 [[Palmerston North]] \u2013 [[Taumarunui]] \u2013 [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] \u2013 [[Auckland]] || {{convert|681|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} || Freight & passenger\n|-\n| '''[[East Coast Main Trunk]]''' || [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] \u2013 [[Morrinsville]] \u2013 [[Kaimai Tunnel]] \u2013 [[Tauranga]] \u2013 [[Kawerau]] || || Freight only\n|-\n| '''[[Midland Line, New Zealand|Midland Line]]''' || [[Rolleston, New Zealand|Rolleston]] \u2013 [[Springfield, New Zealand|Springfield]] \u2013 [[Arthur's Pass]] \u2013 [[Stillwater, West Coast|Stillwater]] \u2013 [[Greymouth]] ||212&nbsp;km (131&nbsp;mi) || Freight & passenger\n|-\n| '''[[Main North Line, New Zealand|Main North Line]]''' || [[Christchurch]] \u2013 [[Kaikoura]] \u2013 [[Blenheim, New Zealand|Blenheim]] \u2013 [[Picton, New Zealand|Picton]] || {{convert|348|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} || Freight & passenger\n|-\n| '''[[Main South Line]]''' || [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]] \u2013 [[Christchurch]] \u2013 [[Timaru]] \u2013 [[Dunedin]] \u2013 [[Invercargill]] || {{convert|601|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} || Freight & passenger (Christchurch \u2013 Rolleston) <br> Freight only (Lyttelton \u2013 Christchurch, Rolleston \u2013 Invercargill)\n|}\nThe last two lines are sometimes referred to as the [[South Island Main Trunk Railway]].\n\n===Secondary main lines===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Route !! Length !! Usage\n|-\n| '''[[Marton - New Plymouth Line]]''' || [[Marton, New Zealand|Marton]] \u2013 [[Wanganui]] \u2013 [[Hawera]] \u2013 [[New Plymouth]] ||  || Freight only\n|-\n| '''[[North Auckland Line]]''' || [[Westfield Junction]] \u2013 [[Newmarket, New Zealand|Newmarket]] \u2013 [[Swanson, New Zealand|Swanson]] \u2013 [[Waitakere]] \u2013 [[Helensville, New Zealand|Helensville]] \u2013 [[Wellsford]] \u2013 [[Whangarei]] \u2013 [[Otiria]] || {{convert|281|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} || Freight and Passengers south of [[Swanson Railway Station|Swanson]]<br> Freight only Swanson to Otiria\n|-\n| '''[[Palmerston North - Gisborne Line]]''' || [[Palmerston North]] \u2013 [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] \u2013 [[Waipukurau]] \u2013 [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]] \u2013 [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] \u2013 [[Muriwai, New Zealand|Muriwai]] \u2013 [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]] || || Freight & Passenger(charter/cruise). Mothballed: Napier to Muriwai 2012. Open: Muriwai to Gisborne, leased by Gisborne Vintage Railway from June 2013<ref>''New Zealand Railway Observer'', June/July 2013 Edition</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiwirail.co.nz/news/184/78/KiwiRail-to-mothball-Napier-Gisborne-line.html|title=KiwiRail to mothball Napier-Gisborne line|website=Kiwirail.co.nz|date=2 October 2012|accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n|- \n| '''[[Stillwater - Westport Line|Stillwater Ngakawau Line]]''' || Stillwater \u2013 [[Reefton]] \u2013 [[Westport, New Zealand|Westport]] \u2013 [[Ngakawau]] || || Freight only\n|-\n| [[Stratford\u2013Okahukura Line]] || [[Stratford, New Zealand|Stratford]] \u2013 [[Whangamomona]] \u2013 [[Okahukura railway station|Okahukura]]||{{convert|144|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} || Passenger: leased to a private operator June 2012.\n|-\n| '''[[Wairarapa Line]]''' || Wellington \u2013 [[Upper Hutt]] \u2013 [[Masterton]] \u2013 [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]] || {{convert|176|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} || Freight & Passenger Wellington to Masterton <br> Freight only Masterton to Woodville\n|}\n\n===Branch lines===\n\n====Northland====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !